UID:74a34b59f462fbf4d464c58836a92afe3122026_3:55:53_PM@campusgroups.com
SUMMARY;ENCODING=QUOTED-PRINTABLE:
LOCATION:Merten Hall room 1204 and on virtually on Zoom , Fairfax, Virginia, United States
URL:https://mason360.gmu.edu/rsvp?id=2296994
DESCRIPTION:The talk focuses on understanding and predicting how global changes and anthropogenic disturbances affect conservation biology. First, I will introduce studies on understanding and predicting invasive species responses to environmental stress and identifying optimal clipping management strategies. In the second study, we studied the role of intraspecific variation in the ongoing range shift of green treefrogs (Hyla cinerea) in response to warming temperature.  We highlighted that population-level SDMs achieved higher predictive accuracy than species-level SDMs.  Finally, I will introduce a recent study on the growing risk of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) exposure in U.S. poultry farms. We predict that more than 45% of poultry farms face increasing exposure risk—rising above 60% under scenarios of high emissions and fragmented development.\n\n\nMeeting Link: https://gmu.zoom.us/meeting/register/_I7zijCATZOs0xfJNNeLYg#/registration\n---\nEvent Details: https://mason360.gmu.edu/rsvp?id=2296994
END:VEVENT
